{"text": "which by (10.69) is the same as (10.63).\n\nWe now comment on the saturation conditions.\n\nFirst, suppose that RNp = p.\n\nBy\n\nmonotonicity of relative entropy (what was just proved) under the application of the channel\n\nR, we find that\n\nD(Np\u2225Nq) \u2265D(RNp\u2225RNq) = D(p\u2225q),\n\n(10.76)\n\nwhere the equality follows from the assumption that RNp = p, and the fact that RNq = q.\n\nThis last statement follows because\n\n(RNq)(x) =\n\nX\n\ny\n\nR(x y)(Nq)(y) =\n\nX\n\ny\n\nN(y x)q(x) = q(x).\n\n(10.77)\n\nThe other implication D(p\u2225q) = D(Np\u2225Nq) \u21d2RNp = p is a consequence of a later devel-\n\nopment, Theorem 10.8.4.\n\n10.7.3\n\nFano\u2019s Inequality\n\nAnother entropy inequality that we consider is Fano\u2019s inequality. This inequality also finds\n\napplication in the converse proof of a coding theorem.\n\nFano\u2019s inequality applies to a general classical communication scenario. Suppose Alice\n\npossesses some random variable X that she transmits to Bob over a noisy communication\n\nchannel. Let pY X(y x) denote the stochastic map corresponding to the noisy communication\n\nchannel. Bob receives a random variable Y from the channel and processes it in some way\n\nto produce his best estimate \u02c6X of the original random variable X. Figure 10.6 depicts this\n\nscenario.\n\nThe natural performance metric of this communication scenario is the probability of error\n\npe \u2261Pr{ \u02c6X \u0338= X}\u2014a low probability of error corresponds to good performance. On the other\n\nc\u20dd2019\n\nMark M. Wilde\u2014Licensed under a Creative Commons Attribution-NonCommercial-ShareAlike 3.0 Unported License\n\n10.7. ENTROPY INEQUALITIES\n\n305\n\nFigure 10.6: The classical communication scenario relevant in Fano\u2019s inequality. Alice transmits a random\n\nvariable X over a noisy channel N, producing a random variable Y . Bob receives Y and processes it according\n\nto some decoding map D to produce his best estimate \u02c6X of Y .\n\nhand, consider the conditional entropy H(X Y ).", "embedding": [-0.0004988768, 0.016583558, 0.052193828, -0.0053188927, 0.00390242, -0.022389747, -0.033871345, -0.019610925, -0.05318902, 0.0693656, 0.078099236, -0.0057577393, 0.0016590437, -0.027706312, -0.0020776559, -0.0076051573, -0.024213415, -0.024467336, -0.019133344, -0.03005557, 0.03998243, -0.0058609643, -0.084081486, -0.018063344, -0.04484754, 0.022567363, 0.038131036, 0.03467911, 0.06891468, 0.054674458, 0.05389772, -0.0076483074, 0.013333501, -0.01879285, 0.019019566, -0.01506654, 0.032226186, 0.0017841171, -0.03889561, -0.046808004, 0.036142096, 0.012180952, 0.01721195, -0.03894596, -0.05139122, -0.009814712, -0.0040768893, 0.0140516, -0.00076283613, -0.094216846, -0.041468203, -0.019097902, 0.019377487, -0.052252576, 0.037285496, 4.939415e-05, 0.010120577, -0.0059840526, 0.021823172, 0.025961252, -0.009065332, -0.01368863, 0.022804007, -0.05712513, -0.0033066731, 0.011701685, 0.0052082096, 8.288831e-05, -0.028973088, -0.018256228, 0.0031634024, -0.0038679985, -0.0616973, -0.020341674, -0.027727613, 0.06295195, 0.010245807, 0.01024412, -0.0491291, 0.020230802, 0.012778752, -0.027050503, 0.0053467257, 0.015249085, 0.002850911, -0.030310791, 0.061810285, -0.035889734, -0.024648668, -0.009854862, -0.0011121513, 0.018009556, -0.0045828177, 0.028563695, -0.015125808, 0.031946648, 0.007854211, 0.00901247, -0.0030713968, 0.013447697, 0.021642061, 0.05904216, -0.010002649, 0.065791056, -0.03311844, 0.037489947, -0.015885469, 0.027129143, -0.015601479, -0.014737887, -0.0054919887, 0.001782051, 0.038067352, 0.0033473668, -0.010594419, 0.024788018, 0.01606525, 0.0015628488, -0.03520128, 0.0018946473, 0.006682022, 0.011859164, 0.043586273, 0.031835098, 0.0030867807, -0.002102161, 0.02986474, 0.021338176, -0.0576839, -0.02122584, 0.005825792, 0.0047110296, -0.009905805, 0.0073930314, 0.011706886, 0.026257595, 0.008306136, 0.030234529, -0.0076528266, -0.010736706, 0.030023254, -0.042919192, -0.018128376, 0.0